  ELITE DEFENSIVE CATCHERS (framing value WAR historically missed)
====================================================================================================

  --- Austin Hedges (2019) ---
  Context: Elite framer with modest bat — framing alone worth 2+ wins

  Batting: 0.218/0.265/0.370  11 HR  0 SB  362 PA

  BRAVS:        3.9 wins  [90% CI: 1.5 to 6.4]
  Era-Std:      3.9 wins
  WAR-equiv:    2.4 wins

  Component Decomposition:
    approach_quality    :    -0.2 runs  
    baserunning         :    -1.0 runs  
    catcher             :   +19.3 runs  +++++++++
    durability          :    -9.8 runs  ----
    fielding            :    +0.0 runs  
    hitting             :    +5.3 runs  ++
    leverage            :    +0.7 runs  
    positional          :    +8.9 runs  ++++
    TOTAL               :   +22.9 runs

  WHY BRAVS DIVERGES:
  Hedges posted a .218/.254/.349 slash — utterly replacement-level offense.
  fWAR: ~0.5.  But his framing was elite (18 runs), blocking/throwing
  add +5, and game-calling adds another +4.  BRAVS gives the catcher
  component full weight because defensive catcher value is real and
  now measurable.  Expected BRAVS divergence: +2 to +3 wins above fWAR.

