  ELITE BASERUNNERS (speed value often underappreciated)
====================================================================================================

  --- Rickey Henderson (1982) ---
  Context: Peak Rickey Henderson — the greatest baserunner ever

  Batting: 0.267/0.419/0.382  10 HR  130 SB  626 PA

  BRAVS:        7.8 wins  [90% CI: 5.2 to 10.3]
  Era-Std:      7.3 wins
  WAR-equiv:    4.8 wins

  Component Decomposition:
    approach_quality    :    +1.8 runs  
    baserunning         :    +6.7 runs  +++
    durability          :    -1.9 runs  
    fielding            :    +0.3 runs  
    hitting             :   +41.6 runs  ++++++++++++++++++++
    leverage            :    +1.6 runs  
    positional          :    -7.4 runs  ---
    TOTAL               :   +43.3 runs

  WHY BRAVS DIVERGES:
  130 SB (42 CS) is a 75.6% success rate — barely above break-even.
  But the VOLUME is staggering.  Even at 75%, 130 attempts generate
  ~14 net baserunning runs from SB/CS alone.  Add GIDP avoidance
  (only 3 GIDP!) and extra bases taken, and the baserunning component
  could be 18+ runs.  His OBP (.398) from 116 walks makes this
  even more impactful.  BRAVS fully captures baserunning value that
  casual observers underrate.

