  EXTREME PARK EFFECTS (Coors deflation / pitcher's park inflation)
====================================================================================================

  --- Larry Walker (1997) ---
  Context: Coors deflation — Walker's numbers were real (mostly)

  Batting: 0.366/0.475/0.720  49 HR  33 SB  613 PA

  BRAVS:        8.9 wins  [90% CI: 7.0 to 10.7]
  Era-Std:     10.3 wins
  WAR-equiv:    5.5 wins

  Component Decomposition:
    approach_quality    :    -1.3 runs  
    baserunning         :    +3.4 runs  +
    durability          :    -0.6 runs  
    fielding            :    +3.3 runs  +
    hitting             :   +60.9 runs  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
    leverage            :    +2.1 runs  +
    positional          :    -6.9 runs  ---
    TOTAL               :   +60.7 runs

  WHY BRAVS DIVERGES:
  Walker hit .366/.452/.720 with 49 HR — but in Coors (PF=1.18).
  WAR applies a park adjustment that reduces his value significantly.
  BRAVS also park-adjusts, but Bayesian shrinkage on the hitting
  component means extreme offensive stats get partially regressed
  toward the mean regardless.  The question: does BRAVS over-correct
  or under-correct for Coors?  Walker was a HOFer for a reason.

