====================================================================================================
  KEY INSIGHTS
====================================================================================================

  1. CATCHER FRAMING IS REAL AND MASSIVE
     Elite framers like Austin Hedges can add 2-3 wins of value that
     traditional WAR completely misses. BRAVS includes framing_runs,
     blocking_runs, throwing_runs, and game_calling_runs as explicit
     components via the catcher module.

  2. LEVERAGE MATTERS FOR RELIEVERS
     A Rivera save in the 9th inning of a 1-run game is worth more
     than a mop-up inning. BRAVS uses gmLI^0.5 as a damped leverage
     multiplier on skill components. This is a middle ground between
     'leverage is everything' and 'an out is an out.' Elite closers
     gain 1-2 wins from this adjustment.

  3. BASERUNNING IS UNDERVALUED IN PUBLIC DISCOURSE
     Rickey Henderson's 130-steal season generates enormous baserunning
     value even at a 75% success rate. GIDP avoidance (Henderson: 3)
     vs. slow players (20+ GIDP) is a 5-8 run swing per season that
     most fans don't think about.

  4. PARK EFFECTS CREATE PERCEPTION DISTORTION
     Coors Field inflates raw stats by ~18%. BRAVS park-adjusts,
     then applies Bayesian shrinkage. This means Walker/Helton get
     less credit than their raw numbers suggest, but more than the
     'lol Coors' dismissal. The truth is in between.

  5. TWO-WAY PLAYERS BREAK EVERY FRAMEWORK
     Ohtani generates value from both hitting and pitching. BRAVS
     simply sums both components — conceptually clean. But the DH
     positional penalty (-17.5 runs/162) on his hitting side arguably
     overcorrects, since he IS playing a demanding position (pitcher).
     Future work: conditional positional adjustment for two-way players.

====================================================================================================
  APPENDIX: LEVERAGE MULTIPLIER EXAMPLES
====================================================================================================

  BRAVS leverage formula: multiplier = gmLI^alpha, alpha=0.50 (sqrt)

    gmLI   Multiplier  Context                                 
  ------------------------------------------------------------
    0.70        0.837  Long reliever, mop-up duty              
    0.95        0.975  Starting pitcher                        
    1.00        1.000  Average leverage (position player)      
    1.35        1.162  Setup man                               
    1.85        1.360  Closer                                  
    2.00        1.414  Elite closer (Gagne 2003)               
    2.15        1.466  Peak Rivera leverage                    

  This means a closer's pitching runs are worth ~40% more than
  a starter's pitching runs on a per-inning basis, reflecting the
  higher stakes of their appearances.


